# .omnijs Files Are OmniAutomation Plug-ins (JavaScript)

Files with the `.omnijs` extension are OmniAutomation plug-in scripts. Always treat them as JavaScript and apply OmniAutomation-specific conventions below.

## Always Consult the Docs

OmniAutomation has its own API, syntax, and global objects. Before writing or editing code, refer to the official reference:
- Full API: https://omni-automation.com
- OmniFocus-specific: https://omni-automation.com/omnifocus/
- `URL.FetchRequest`: https://omni-automation.com/url/fetch-request.html
- `Credentials`: https://omni-automation.com/shared/credentials.html
- `Form` / `Form.Field`: https://omni-automation.com/shared/form.html
- `PlugIn` / libraries: https://omni-automation.com/shared/plugin.html

## Plug-in File Structure

Every plug-in starts with a JSON descriptor in a block comment, followed by an IIFE that returns an `action`:

```js
/*{
    "type": "action",
    "targets": ["omnifocus"],
    "identifier": "com.example.my-plugin",
    "version": "1.0",
    "label": "My Action"
}*/
(() => {
    const action = new PlugIn.Action(function(selection, sender) { ... });
    action.validate = function(selection, sender) { return true; };
    return action;
})();
```

## Key Global APIs (do NOT polyfill or import — they are injected by the runtime)

| API | Purpose |
|-----|---------|
| `PlugIn.Action` | Define the action handler |
| `PlugIn.find(id)` / `.library(name)` | Load a shared library plug-in |
| `URL.FetchRequest.fromString(url)` | Create an HTTP request (NOT `fetch`) |
| `request.fetch()` | Execute the request (returns a Promise) |
| `response.statusCode` / `response.bodyString` | Parse the response |
| `Credentials` | Securely store/retrieve tokens (keychain-backed) |
| `credentials.write(service, user, password)` | Store a credential |
| `credentials.read(service)` | Returns `{user, password}` or `null` |
| `credentials.remove(service)` | Delete stored credential |
| `Form` / `Form.Field.Password` / `Form.Field.String` | Build input dialogs |
| `Alert` | Show alerts and confirmations |
| `app.platformName` | `"macOS"` or `"iOS"` |
| `app.controlKeyDown` / `app.optionKeyDown` | Modifier key state |
| `TextAutocapitalizationType` | Autocap control for iOS form fields |

## Network Requests

Use `URL.FetchRequest` — never `fetch`, `XMLHttpRequest`, or `axios`:

```js
const request = URL.FetchRequest.fromString("https://example.com/api")
request.method = "GET"
request.cache = "no-cache"
request.headers = { "Authorization": "Bearer " + token }
const response = await request.fetch()
// response.statusCode, response.bodyString
```

## Credential Handling

Auth tokens must be stored via `Credentials`, never hardcoded:

```js
const credentials = new Credentials()
credentials.write("my-service", "username", token)
const cred = credentials.read("my-service") // { user, password }
```

## Secret Manager Library

A centralized credential manager is available at `com.gmail.romansavrulin.secret-manager-library`. Load it:

```js
const sm = PlugIn.find("com.gmail.romansavrulin.secret-manager-library").library("secret-manager-library");
```

### authenticatedFetch — preferred way to make HTTP requests

Use `sm.authenticatedFetch(url, options)` instead of raw `URL.FetchRequest`. It transparently injects auth headers when the URL matches a registered service:

```js
const response = await sm.authenticatedFetch("https://api.github.com/user", {
    method: "GET",
    headers: { "Accept": "application/json" }
});
```

- `options`: `{ method, cache, headers, bodyString }` — all optional, defaults to GET / no-cache
- If the URL origin matches a registered service, auth headers are merged automatically
- If credentials are missing for a matched service, throws `MissingCredentials`
- If no service matches, performs a plain unauthenticated fetch

### Registry API

| Method | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| `sm.addService(id, label, urlPattern, authType)` | Register a service |
| `sm.removeService(id)` | Remove service + credentials |
| `sm.getService(id)` | Get single registry entry |
| `sm.listServices()` | List all entries with `hasCredential` flag |
| `sm.setCredential(id, user, password)` | Store secret in keychain |
| `sm.getCredential(id)` | Read `{user, password}` or null |
| `sm.findServiceForURL(urlString)` | Match URL to service by origin |

Auth types: `bearer`, `oauth`, `basic`, `cookie`, `custom-header`

### Management UI

Run the "Manage Secrets" action (`ManageSecrets.omnijs`) to list, add, edit, or delete services and their credentials interactively.

## URL Resolver Library

An extensible URL-to-title resolver is available at `com.gmail.romansavrulin.url-resolver-library`. Load it:

```js
const resolver = PlugIn.find("com.gmail.romansavrulin.url-resolver-library").library("url-resolver-library");
```

### resolve(url) -- get a page/resource title from any URL

```js
const title = await resolver.resolve("https://github.com/user/repo/issues/42");
// -> "Fix login bug #42"
```

Runs a chain of auto-discovered resolvers in priority order, then any manually added resolvers, then the built-in HTML fallback (og:title / twitter:title / title tag). Auth is handled transparently via `sm.authenticatedFetch`.

### Auto-Discovery of Resolver Modules

Resolver modules are separate `.omnijs` library files auto-discovered at resolve time via `PlugIn.all`. Any plug-in whose identifier starts with `com.gmail.romansavrulin.resolver-` is loaded automatically.

Built-in resolver modules:
- `resolver-github.omnijs` — GitHub repos, issues, PRs, commits via REST API
- `resolver-jira.omnijs` — Jira issues via REST API
- `resolver-youtube.omnijs` — YouTube videos via oEmbed
- `resolver-atushka.omnijs` — Yandex Atushka posts via BFF batch API
- `resolver-startrek.omnijs` — Yandex StartrekTracker issues via v3 REST API

To add a new resolver, create a file like `resolver-myservice.omnijs`:

```js
/*{
    "author": "Roman Savrulin",
    "targets": ["omnifocus", "omnigraffle", "omnioutliner", "omniplan"],
    "type": "library",
    "identifier": "com.gmail.romansavrulin.resolver-myservice",
    "version": "0.1"
}*/
(() => {
    "use strict";
    var lib = new PlugIn.Library(new Version("1.0"));

    lib.resolverName = "MyService";  // must use resolverName, not name (read-only on PlugIn.Library)
    lib.priority = 10;               // lower = higher priority; HTML fallback is 9999

    lib.matches = function (url) {
        return /myservice\.com/.test(url);
    };

    lib.resolve = async function (url, fetchFn) {
        // fetchFn = sm.authenticatedFetch (auth injected automatically)
        // Return string (title), null (fall through), or throw (hard error)
        const resp = await fetchFn(apiUrl, { headers: { "Accept": "application/json" } });
        return JSON.parse(resp.bodyString).title;
    };

    return lib;
})();
```

### Resolver API Response Structures

**GitHub** (`api.github.com/repos/{owner}/{repo}/issues/{num}`, etc.):
```json
{ "title": "...", "full_name": "owner/repo", "description": "...", "commit": { "message": "..." } }
```

**Jira** (`{base}/rest/api/2/issue/{KEY}?fields=summary`):
```json
{ "fields": { "summary": "Issue title" } }
```

**YouTube** (`youtube.com/oembed?url=...&format=json`):
```json
{ "title": "Video title" }
```

**Atushka** (`at.yandex-team.ru/esoc/hub/bff/api/v1/batch/posts/?postIds={id}`):
URL pattern: `yandex-team.ru/atushka/post/{id}`
```json
{
  "success": {
    "<postId>": {
      "postId": "...",
      "content": { "title": "...", "snippet": "...", "renderedHtml": "..." },
      "structuredContent": { "title": "...", "snippet": "...", "widgets": [...] },
      "postType": "TEXT"
    }
  },
  "errors": {}
}
```
Title is extracted from `success[postId].content.title`, falling back to `success[postId].structuredContent.title`.

**StartrekTracker** (`st-api.yandex-team.ru/v3/issues/{KEY}`):
URL pattern: `st.yandex-team.ru/{KEY}` (e.g. `SAMSARAVTEAM-37108`)
Response may be an object or an array; the resolver handles both.
```json
{
  "self": "https://st-api.yandex-team.ru/v3/issues/TREK-9844",
  "id": "593cd211ef7e8a33********",
  "key": "TREK-9844",
  "summary": "subtask",
  "description": "...",
  "type": { "key": "task", "display": "..." },
  "priority": { "key": "normal", "display": "..." },
  "status": { "key": "open", "display": "..." },
  "parent": { "key": "JUNE-2", "display": "Task" },
  "project": { "primary": { "display": "..." } }
}
```
Title is formatted as `KEY: summary`.

### Shared HTML Helpers

The core library exposes utilities for resolver modules that need HTML parsing:
- `resolver.decodeEntities(text)` — decode HTML entities
- `resolver.extractTitle(html)` — extract title from og:title, twitter:title, or `<title>` tag

### Resolver Interface (runtime addResolver)

Custom resolvers can also be added at runtime with `resolver.addResolver(obj)`:

```js
resolver.addResolver({
    name: "MyService",
    matches: function(url) { return /myservice\.com/.test(url); },
    resolve: async function(url, fetchFn) { ... }
});
```

Return contract: non-empty string = success, null = try next resolver, throw = stop with error.

Other methods: `removeResolver(name)`, `listResolvers()`.

## Security Notes

- Tokens and secrets must always go through `Credentials` (keychain-backed)
- Use `sm.authenticatedFetch()` for any URL that may need authentication
- `URL.FetchRequest` calls send data over the network — review headers carefully
- `console.log(response.bodyString)` may log sensitive data; avoid in production
